## Task 3 ARP: Bridging Layer 3 to Layer 2

- IP packets are encapsulated in Ethernet/WiFi frames. To send a frame, the sender must know the MAC address of the target.
- MAC basics: 48-bit number, shown in hexadecimal (e.g., 7C:DF:A1:D3:8C:5C).
- Ethernet frame header includes: Destination MAC, Source MAC, Type (IPv4).
- ARP (Address Resolution Protocol): Used to discover MAC addresses associated with IPs.
Example: Host 192.168.66.89 asks “Who has 192.168.66.1?” → broadcast. Target replies with its MAC address.
tcpdump output example:
- Code
Request who-has 192.168.66.1 tell 192.168.66.89
Reply 192.168.66.1 is-at 44:df:65:d8:fe:6c
ARP packets are encapsulated directly in Ethernet frames, not IP/UDP.
Debate: Layer 2 vs Layer 3 classification.
- Takeaway: ARP translates IP (Layer 3) into MAC (Layer 2).

