## Findings

- DHCP automates configuration, preventing conflicts.
- ARP enables IP-to-MAC resolution, critical for Layer 2 communication.
- ICMP provides visibility into connectivity and routing paths.
- Routing protocols ensure scalability and efficiency across the Internet.
- NAT extends IPv4 usability, enabling private networks to connect globally.

## Mitigation / Best Practices

- Use DHCP for mobile devices; static IPs for servers.
- Monitor ARP traffic to detect spoofing attacks.
- Restrict ICMP if necessary, but allow controlled diagnostics.
- Secure routing protocols to prevent hijacking or misconfiguration.
- Apply NAT carefully, with proper firewall rules.
- Transition to IPv6 where possible to avoid long-term IPv4 limitations.

